Key.Rationale: The conjunction “and” appropriately separates the last two nouns in the series, “radio” and “other media.”
“And with” disrupt the parallel structure of the series of three nouns (“television,” “radio,” “[other] media”) introduced by “competing with.”
“And also” disrupt the parallel structure of the series of three nouns (“television,” “radio,” “[other] media”) introduced by “competing with.”
“And competing with” disrupt the parallel structure of the series of three nouns (“television,” “radio,” “[other] media”) introduced by “competing with.”

SubTopics: Rhetorical Synthesis, for which students must strategically integrate provided information and ideas on a topic to form an effective sentence achieving a specified rhetorical aim.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L2 of the passage.
The writer wants to include a quotation by Hersey that supports the topic of the passage. Which choice best accomplishes this goal?

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't support the topic of the passage. A sense of wholeness and accomplishment doesn't support the idea of making children's literature more interesting.

B.Choice: interesting, since “learning starts with failure; the first failure is the beginning of education.”

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't support the topic of the passage. The value of failure doesn't support the idea of making children's literature more interesting.

C.Choice: interesting because “journalism allows its readers to witness history; fiction gives its readers an opportunity to live it.”

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't support the topic of the passage. A difference between journalism and fiction doesn't support the idea of making children's literature more interesting.

D.Choice: interesting with “drawings like those of the wonderfully imaginative geniuses among children's illustrators.”

Key.Rationale: The topic of the passage is the creation of The Cat in the Hat as a means of getting children more interested in learning to read. Hersey's suggestion that one way of making children's books more interesting was to use “drawings like those of the wonderfully imaginative geniuses among children's illustrators” best supports the topic of the passage.

SubTopics: Boundaries, for which students must edit text to ensure that sentences are conventionally complete.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L3 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The comma after “Spaulding” is paired correctly with the comma after “Mifflin” to set off grammatically nonessential information.
A comma is needed after “Spaulding” to set off the nonessential phrase that ends with “Mifflin.”
Placing a comma after “Spaulding” and after “director” wrongly indicates that “the director” could be deleted without changing the meaning of the sentence.
A dash can't be paired with a comma to set off grammatically nonessential information.

SubTopics: Boundaries, for which students must edit text to ensure that sentences are conventionally complete.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L4 of the passage.
Which choice most effectively combines the sentences at the emphasized portion?

Key.Rationale: This choice most effectively combines the sentences at the emphasized portion because it's concise and correctly indicates that Spaulding saw a need for appealing books for beginning readers at the same time that he thought he knew who should write one.

“Namely” indicates that a more specific restatement of an earlier point or an example will follow. In this case, what follows the idea that Spaulding saw a need for appealing books is his thought about who should write one.
The repetition of Spaulding's name is unnecessary.
The adverb “meanwhile” is redundant; the conjunction “and” is sufficient to indicate that Spaulding had two thoughts simultaneously.

SubTopics: Rhetorical Synthesis, for which students must strategically integrate provided information and ideas on a topic to form an effective sentence achieving a specified rhetorical aim.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L5 of the passage.
Which revision best supports the information that follows in the sentence?

Key.Rationale: Geisel's long relationship with Spaulding doesn't support the idea that Geisel was an experienced writer and illustrator.

B.Choice: acquired a reputation for perfectionism and for setting high standards for his work,

Key.Rationale: Geisel's reputation for perfectionism and for setting high standards doesn't support the idea that Geisel was an experienced writer and illustrator.

C.Choice: been interested in politics before breaking into the genre of children's literature,

Key.Rationale: Geisel's interest in politics doesn't support the idea that Geisel was an experienced writer and illustrator.

D.Choice: published nine children's books and having received three nominations for the prestigious Caldecott Medal,

Key.Rationale: This choice, which indicates that Geisel published nine children's books and received three nominations for the prestigious Caldecott Medal, supports the information that follows in the sentence about Geisel being an experienced writer and illustrator.

SubTopics: Transitions, for which students must determine the most effective transition word or phrase to logically connect information and ideas in a text.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L6 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: “However” correctly indicates that even though Geisel was an experienced writer and illustrator, the new project presented him with an obstacle.

This transitional phrase shows the true relationship between the challenging nature of the new project and Geisel's experience. “For example” indicates that what follows is an instance of what was stated in the previous sentence.

This transitional word  shows the true relationship between the challenging nature of the new project and Geisel's experience. “Furthermore” indicates that what follows is an additional to what was stated in the previous sentence.

This transitional phrase shows the true relationship between the challenging nature of the new project and Geisel's experience. “At any rate” indicates that what follows is unrelated to what was stated in the previous sentence.

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L7 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: “Geisel's story” can't be described as being “on the verge of giving up.”

B.Choice: an image that Geisel finally hit upon became the basis of his story:

Key.Rationale: “An image” can't be described as being “on the verge of giving up.”

C.Choice: Geisel finally hit upon the image that became the basis for his story:

Key.Rationale: The introductory phrase “on the verge of giving up” doesn't have its own subject. Instead, the subject appears at the beginning of the sentence's main clause and makes clear what is being described in the introductory phrase. “Geisel” is the logical subject of the sentence because he can be described as being “on the verge of giving up.”

D.Choice: the story was finally based on an image that Geisel hit upon:

Key.Rationale: “The story” can't be described as being “on the verge of giving up.”

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L8 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice is repetitive. “Duration” and “long” unnecessarily repeat the idea that nine months had passed.

B.Choice: After thirty-six weeks—or nine months—had passed,

Key.Rationale: This choice is repetitive. “Thirty-six weeks” unnecessarily repeat the idea that nine months had passed.

C.Choice: After a length of nine months had elapsed,

Key.Rationale: This choice is repetitive. “Length” unnecessarily repeat the idea that nine months had passed.
This choice concisely indicates that it took Geisel nine months to complete The Cat in the Hat.

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L9 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: “Is captivated” is a singular verb that does't agree in number with the plural subject “children.”
“Was captivated” is a singular verb that does't agree in number with the plural subject “children.”
“Has been captivated” is a singular verb that does't agree in number with the plural subject “children.”

The emphasized portion should be deleted because it isn't necessary. Since “were entertained” appears earlier in the sentence, the past participle “captivated” is sufficient without the repetition of “were.”

SubTopics: Boundaries, for which students must edit text to ensure that sentences are conventionally complete.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L10 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: A period can't be used in this way to separate an introductory dependent phrase from an independent clause.
A semicolon can't be used in this way to separate an introductory dependent phrase from an independent clause.
The comma after “followed” is used correctly to separate the dependent phrase “in the years that followed” from the independent clause that begins with “many.”
A dash can't be used in this way to separate an introductory dependent phrase from an independent clause.

SubTopics: Rhetorical Synthesis, for which students must strategically integrate provided information and ideas on a topic to form an effective sentence achieving a specified rhetorical aim.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L11 of the passage.
The writer wants a conclusion that restates the main themes of the passage. Which choice best accomplishes this goal?

Key.Rationale: The idea that the best proof of The Cat in the Hat's success is its limited vocabulary and appealing word choices doesn't restate the main themes of the passage.

B.Choice: impressive worldwide sales that continue to remain high to this day.

Key.Rationale: The idea that the best proof of The Cat in the Hat's success is its impressive worldwide sales  doesn't restate the main themes of the passage.

C.Choice: enduring ability to delight children and engage them in learning how to read.

Key.Rationale: This choice indicates that The Cat in the Hat's success is attributable to its enduring ability to delight children and engage them in learning how to read. This idea restates the main themes of the passage, which are the need to make books appealing to beginning readers and the importance of engaging those readers through interesting plots and illustrations.

D.Choice: important role in the history of illustration in the twentieth century.

Key.Rationale: The idea that the best proof of The Cat in the Hat's success is its important role in the history of twentieth-century illustration doesn't restate the main themes of the passage.

Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't maintain parallelism in the sentence. “When they pick up litter” doesn't contain gerunds.
This choice doesn't maintain parallelism in the sentence. “To pick up litter” doesn't contain gerunds.
This choice doesn't maintain parallelism in the sentence. “Litter collection” doesn't contain gerunds.
The gerund “picking up” is parallel in structure to the other gerunds in the sentence, “helping” and “working.”

SubTopics: Transitions, for which students must determine the most effective transition word or phrase to logically connect information and ideas in a text.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L2 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The transitional phrase “by its very definition” points to the criticism in the previous paragraph that when volunteering is compulsory, it's no longer volunteerism.
The reference to general work doesn't highlight the criticism of compulsory volunteering mentioned in the previous paragraph.
The reference to students doesn't highlight the criticism of compulsory volunteering mentioned in the previous paragraph.
The reference to communities in need doesn't highlight the criticism of compulsory volunteering mentioned in the previous paragraph.

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L3 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: “Officials'” is a plural possessive noun, but nothing belongs to the officials in this sentence.
“Students” is a plural noun, but the plural possessive noun “students'” is needed to indicate that the choice is supposed to belong to students.
“Student's” is a singular possessive noun, but the plural possessive noun “students'” is needed to show that the choice is supposed to belong to multiple students.

The plural noun “officials” correctly refers to the people who require students to give up time for nonprofit activities. Additionally, the plural possessive noun “students'” indicates that the choice to give up personal time is supposed to belong to multiple students.

SubTopics: Boundaries, for which students must edit text to ensure that sentences are conventionally complete.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L4 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice is repetitive. Since proponents are people who support a cause, describing proponents of compulsory volunteering as being in favor of it creates redundancy.
This choice is repetitive. Since proponents are people who support a cause, describing proponents of compulsory volunteering as advocating it.
This choice is clear and concise and doesn't repeat the idea of proponents that begins the sentence.
This choice is repetitive. Since proponents are people who support a cause, describing proponents of compulsory volunteering as being advocates creates redundancy.

SubTopics: Rhetorical Synthesis, for which students must strategically integrate provided information and ideas on a topic to form an effective sentence achieving a specified rhetorical aim.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L5 of the passage.
Which revision provides a supporting example that is most similar to the examples already in the sentence?

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't provide a supporting example that is similar to the examples in the sentence. Increasingly busy schedules isn't a benefit of volunteering.

B.Choice: a closer connection with their community.

Key.Rationale: This choice, a closer connection with their community, is a benefit of volunteering and provides a supporting example that is most similar to the other examples of benefits offered in the sentence: increased self-esteem and better relationship-building skills.

C.Choice: less time spent engaging in social activities.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't provide a supporting example that is similar to the examples in the sentence. Less time spent engaging in social activities isn't a benefit of volunteering.
This choice doesn't provide a supporting example that is similar to the examples in the sentence. Little increase in academic achievement isn't a benefit of volunteering.

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L6 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The verb “effect” generally means “to bring about,” which doesn't make sense in the sentence.

The infinitive “[to] affect” parallels the earlier infinitive “[to] volunteer” (“are more likely to volunteer,” “[are more likely to] affect”). Moreover, “affect,” meaning “to influence,” is used correctly to indicate that students who do community service positively influence society.
The noun “effect” means “result,” which doesn't make sense in the sentence.
The singular verb “affects” doesn't work here, where the infinitive “affect” is required.

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L7 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: “Mandatory” is the most precise word to use when describing the volunteering that students are required to do.

The meaning of this word doesn't fit the context of the sentence. “Coercive” suggest that threats or force are used to make someone do something. This word is not appropriate to use when describing the volunteering that students are required to do.

The meaning of this word doesn't fit the context of the sentence. “Forcible” suggest that threats or force are used to make someone do something. This word is not appropriate to use when describing the volunteering that students are required to do.

The meaning of this word doesn't fit the context of the sentence. “Imperative” suggests that something is very important or necessary. This word is not appropriate to use when describing the volunteering that students are required to do.

SubTopics: Boundaries, for which students must edit text to ensure that sentences are conventionally complete.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L8 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: A comma can't be used by itself to join two independent clauses.
It's unnecessary to place a comma between the adverb “then” and the verb “did,” which the adverb describes.
No punctuation is needed to separate the subject “they” from the adverb “then.”

The semicolon is used correctly to separate the independent clause that begins with “she” from the independent clause that begins with “they.” In addition, this choice contains no unnecessary punctuation.

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L9 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice illogically compares “hours” to students (“they”).
“Than did students who were” results in a logical comparison between two types of students: those who were required to volunteer (“they then did”) and those who weren't (“than did those”).
This choice illogically compares “hours” to students (“they”).
This choice results in a nonstandard expression; “less” is already comparative, meaning that “compared with” isn't appropriate.

SubTopics: Rhetorical Synthesis, for which students must strategically integrate provided information and ideas on a topic to form an effective sentence achieving a specified rhetorical aim.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L10 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't effectively set up the point made in the next sentence. The ideas that schools have to recognize that not all students are equally well suited to the same activities doesn't set up the point that students willingly volunteer when schools connect them to volunteer opportunities and organizations.

B.Choice: should allow students to spend their time participating in athletics and other extracurricular activities.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't effectively set up the point made in the next sentence. The ideas that schools have to recognize that not all students should allow students to spend their time participating in athletics and other extracurricular activities doesn't set up the point that students willingly volunteer when schools connect them to volunteer opportunities and organizations.

C.Choice: should focus on offering arrangements that make volunteering an easy and attractive choice.

Key.Rationale: The idea that schools should focus on offering arrangements that make volunteering an easy and attractive choice most effectively sets up the point made in the next sentence: more students willingly volunteer when schools tell them about volunteering opportunities and connect them with organizations.

D.Choice: are advised to recognize the limits of their ability to influence their students.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't effectively set up the point made in the next sentence. The ideas that schools have to recognize that not all students are advised to recognize the limits of their ability to influence their students doesn't set up the point that students willingly volunteer when schools connect them to volunteer opportunities and organizations.

SubTopics: Rhetorical Synthesis, for which students must strategically integrate provided information and ideas on a topic to form an effective sentence achieving a specified rhetorical aim.
Content: Refer to location L11 of the passage and think about the passage as a whole.
The writer wants a conclusion that states the main claim of the passage. Which choice best accomplishes this goal?

A.Choice: It is imperative that schools do their part to find volunteers for the many worthwhile organizations in the United States.

Key.Rationale: The idea that schools should find volunteers for organizations in the United States doesn't state the passage's main claim that schools that don't require volunteering produce more engaged, enthusiastic volunteers.

B.Choice: Schools that do this will produce more engaged, enthusiastic volunteers than schools that require volunteer work.

Key.Rationale: This choice provides a conclusion that states the main claim of the passage: schools that don't make volunteering compulsory will produce more engaged, enthusiastic volunteers than will schools that require volunteer work.

C.Choice: Studies in the fields of psychology and economics have revolutionized researchers' understanding of volunteerism.

Key.Rationale: The idea that that psychological and economic studies have revolutionized understandings of volunteerism doesn't state the passage's main claim that schools that don't require volunteering produce more engaged, enthusiastic volunteers.

D.Choice: Studies in the fields of psychology and economics have revolutionized researchers' understanding of volunteerism.

Key.Rationale: The idea that students should choose charitable work that suits their interests and values doesn't state the passage's main claim that schools that don't require volunteering produce more engaged, enthusiastic volunteers.

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L1 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't describe a belief that originated in the past and continues in the present. The present progressive tense verb “are believing” isn't appropriate to use in a case that requires a present perfect tense verb.

This choice doesn't describe a belief that originated in the past and continues in the present. The future progressive tense verb “will be believing” isn't appropriate to use in a case that requires a present perfect tense verb.

The present perfect tense verb “have believed” correctly indicates that scientists in the past believed that the corpus callosum enables complex tasks and that scientists continue to hold this belief in the present.

This choice doesn't describe a belief that originated in the past and continues in the present. The simple present tense verb “believe” isn't appropriate to use in a case that requires a present perfect tense verb.

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L2 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: This choice concisely defines handedness without unnecessarily repeating the ideas of preference or consistency.

B.Choice: and favor the use of one hand over the other,

Key.Rationale: “Favor the use of” repeats the idea of “prefer,” which appears earlier in the sentence.

C.Choice: one hand over the other that could be chosen,

Key.Rationale: “Could be chosen” repeats the idea of “prefer,” which appears earlier in the sentence.

D.Choice: one hand on a regular basis,

Key.Rationale: “On a regular basis” is synonymous with “consistently,” which also appears earlier in the sentence.

SubTopics: Boundaries, for which students must edit text to ensure that sentences are conventionally complete.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L3 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: No punctuation is necessary between the noun “trait” and the preposition “other than.”
A comma isn't necessary to separate the noun “trait” from the phrase that follows.
A semicolon isn't necessary to separate the noun “trait” from the phrase that follows.
A colon isn't necessary to separate the noun “trait” from the phrase that follows.

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L4 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: “Links as” isn't idiomatic when indicating that two things are directly related to each other.

The phrase “correlates with” is idiomatic when indicating that two things are directly related to each other. In the passage, handedness in marsupials is believed to be related to the trait of bipedalism in those mammals.
“Correlates from” isn't idiomatic when indicating that two things are directly related to each other.
““Links on” isn't idiomatic when indicating that two things are directly related to each other.

SubTopics: Rhetorical Synthesis, for which students must strategically integrate provided information and ideas on a topic to form an effective sentence achieving a specified rhetorical aim.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L5 of the passage.
Which revision accurately reflects the information in the graph?

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't accurately reflect the information in the graph.

B.Choice: scores of 0 or less indicated a left-forelimb preference and positive scores indicated a lack of forelimb preference.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't accurately reflect the information in the graph.

C.Choice: positive scores indicated a lack of forelimb preference and negative scores indicated a right-forelimb preference.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't accurately reflect the information in the graph.

D.Choice: positive scores indicated a left-forelimb preference and negative scores indicated a right-forelimb preference.

Key.Rationale: According to the graph, positive mean handedness index scores indicated a left-forelimb preference and negative scores indicated a right-forelimb preference.

SubTopics: Boundaries, for which students must edit text to ensure that sentences are conventionally complete.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L6 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: The comma needs to be placed immediately before the conjunction “and,” not after it.
The comma after “kangaroo” and before the conjunction “and” is used correctly to separate the last two items, “red kangaroo” and “brush-tailed bettong,” in the list of bipedal marsupials.
A semicolon isn't used to separate individual items in a simple list.
A dash isn't used to separate items in a list, and the comma after “and” is unnecessary.

SubTopics: Rhetorical Synthesis, for which students must strategically integrate provided information and ideas on a topic to form an effective sentence achieving a specified rhetorical aim.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L7 of the passage.
Which revision most accurately reflects the data in the graph?

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't accurately reflect the data in the graph. The four bipedal marsupials didn't have positive mean handedness index values less than 0.2.

B.Choice: positive mean handedness index values greater than 0.6

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't accurately reflect the data in the graph. The four bipedal marsupials didn't have positive mean handedness index values greater than 0.6.

C.Choice: positive mean handedness index values between 0.4 and 0.6

Key.Rationale: According to the graph, the four bipedal marsupials had positive mean handedness index values between 0.4 and 0.6, which revealed their preference for using their left forelimbs.
This choice doesn't accurately reflect the data in the graph. The four bipedal marsupials didn't have mean handedness index values of 0.

SubTopics: Transitions, for which students must determine the most effective transition word or phrase to logically connect information and ideas in a text.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L8 of the passage.
Which revision provides the best transition from the previous paragraph?

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't provide a transition from the previous paragraph. The introductory phrases “having four feet” doesn't establish a connection between the discussion of bipedal marsupials' forelimb preference in the previous paragraph and quadrupedal marsupials' forelimb preference in this paragraph.

This choice doesn't provide a transition from the previous paragraph. The introductory phrases “like most other mammals” doesn't establish a connection between the discussion of bipedal marsupials' forelimb preference in the previous paragraph and quadrupedal marsupials' forelimb preference in this paragraph.

C.Choice: In contrast to their bipedal counterparts,

Key.Rationale: The transitional phrase “in contrast to” provides the best transition from the previous paragraph, which illustrates bipedal marsupials' forelimb preference, to this paragraph, which discusses how quadrupedal marsupials differ from their bipedal counterparts by not showing a strong forelimb preference.

D.Choice: While using their forelimbs for eating,

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't provide a transition from the previous paragraph. The introductory phrases “while using their forelimbs for eating” doesn't establish a connection between the discussion of bipedal marsupials' forelimb preference in the previous paragraph and quadrupedal marsupials' forelimb preference in this paragraph.

SubTopics: Rhetorical Synthesis, for which students must strategically integrate provided information and ideas on a topic to form an effective sentence achieving a specified rhetorical aim.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L9 of the passage.
Which revision presents a main claim of the passage?

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't present a main claim of the passage. The passage isn't about how kangaroos still don't exhibit handedness to the extent that humans do.

B.Choice: For the marsupials in the study, then, handedness seems to be associated with bipedalism.

Key.Rationale: A main claim of the passage is that scientists now believe there's a correlation between bipedalism and handedness in marsupials. This choice, by mentioning that bipedal marsupials in the study demonstrated handedness, references this main claim.

C.Choice: There are many things scientists do not understand about the marsupial brain.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't present a main claim of the passage. The passage isn't about the many things scientists don't understand about the marsupial brain.

D.Choice: Additional studies on this phenomenon will need to be performed with other mammals.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't present a main claim of the passage. The passage isn't about additional studies on the phenomenon of handedness that will need to be performed with other mammals.

SubTopics: Form, Structure, and Sense, for which students must edit text to conform to conventional usage (e.g., agreement, verb tense/aspect).
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L10 of the passage.
Which revision most effectively improves the quality of writing in the passage or makes the passage conform to the conventions of standard written English.

Key.Rationale: “Whom” is used to refer to people, not concepts.
“Which” is a standard relative pronoun in reference to a concept such as a task.
“What” isn't a typical relative pronoun and isn't idiomatic in context (“tasks in what handedness may confer an evolutionary advantage”).
“Whose” nonsensically suggests that tasks have handedness.

SubTopics: Rhetorical Synthesis, for which students must strategically integrate provided information and ideas on a topic to form an effective sentence achieving a specified rhetorical aim.
Content: Refer to the emphasized portion at location L11 of the passage.
The writer wants to conclude the passage by recalling a topic from the first paragraph that requires additional research. Which choice best accomplishes this goal?

Key.Rationale: No change is needed because this choice concludes the passage by recalling a topic from the first paragraph that requires additional research: scientists' enduring question about how the left and right hemispheres of marsupials' brains communicate since these mammals lack a corpus callosum.

B.Choice: though researchers should not neglect the sizable minority of humans who are left handed.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't conclude the passage by recalling a topic from the first paragraph that requires additional research. The first paragraph doesn't refer to the minority of humans who are left handed.

C.Choice: and scientists believe that studies like this one may someday yield insights into the causes of certain neurological disorders.

Key.Rationale: This choice doesn't conclude the passage by recalling a topic from the first paragraph that requires additional research. The first paragraph doesn't refer to the fact that studies like this one may someday yield insights into the causes of neurological disorders.

SubTopics: Transitions, for which students must determine the most effective transition word or phrase to logically connect information and ideas in a text.

Key.Rationale: “Despite these findings” suggests that regardless of the percentages, more companies should consider providing tuition assistance, which is illogical.
The information that follows in the sentence isn't additional to the 2014 study.

“Although these levels are impressive” provides the most effective transition from the previous sentence, which indicates the percent of surveyed companies that provide employees with tuition assistance, to the information that follows in this sentence, that even more companies should consider providing such assistance.

Key.Rationale: The issue of whether companies want or don't want to provide tuition assistance isn't mentioned in the previous sentence.

Key.Rationale: The plural possessive noun “workers'” and “opportunities'” should be the plural nouns “workers” and “opportunities,” since nothing belongs to the workers or opportunities in the sentence.
The plural possessive noun “workers'” and “opportunities'” should be the plural nouns “workers” and “opportunities,” since nothing belongs to the workers or opportunities in the sentence.

The plural noun “workers” correctly indicates that companies have more than one worker. The plural noun “opportunities” indicates that employers offer workers multiple chances for personal and professional development.

This choice most effectively combines the sentences at the emphasized portion because the pronoun “which” creates a relative clause (“which ... workers”) that clearly and concisely describes “retain.”
“That” doesn't have a clear antecedent and therefore creates a vague sentence.

Key.Rationale: Placing a period or a semicolon after “degrees” results in a rhetorically ineffective sentence fragment.

No punctuation is needed between the noun and subordinate conjunction. (Although colons can be used to introduce additional explanatory information in a sentence, they're not typically used between a main clause and a dependent clause beginning with a subordinate conjunction such as “because.”)

The subordinate conjunction “because” begins the dependent clause “because their new qualifications give them opportunities for advancement within the company.” No punctuation is needed to separate this dependent clause from the independent clause that directly precedes it.
Placing a period or a semicolon after “degrees” results in a rhetorically ineffective sentence fragment.

SubTopics: Transitions, for which students must determine the most effective transition word or phrase to logically connect information and ideas in a text.
Content: Think about the passage as a whole.
The writer wants to insert the following sentence.
:ibox:Still, since securing an excellent workforce is crucial to a business's success, employers should give serious thought to investing in reimbursement programs.
To make the passage most logical, the sentence should be placed immediately after the last sentence in paragraph

Key.Rationale: Placing the sentence at the end of paragraph 1 would result in an illogical passage.
Placing the sentence at the end of paragraph 2 would result in an illogical passage.
Placing the sentence at the end of paragraph 3 would result in an illogical passage.

To make the passage most logical, the sentence should be placed after the last sentence of paragraph 4. The use of “still” in the inserted sentence indicates that a contrast to what was stated previously will follow. Paragraph 4 ends by stating that tuition reimbursement may not be appropriate in all cases, and the inserted sentence indicates that despite this fact, employers should give serious thought to investing in reimbursement programs. Moreover, the inserted sentence restates the passage's main claim and, therefore, effectively concludes the passage.
